Gollum attenuatus
was initially known only from New Zealand seas (
Garrick 1954
,
Compagno 1988
) where it has since been collected widely using bottom longlines; north to the Wanganella Bank (
32 ° 35 ’S
) and the Three Kings Ridge (
28 ° 10 ’S
) (
Yano, 1993 a
), and south to at least the Snares Islands (
48 ° 54 ’S
) (
Yano, 1993 b
), where the primary depth interval for more than
750 specimens
was from 500–600 m (
Yano, 1993 b
). More recently, material was collected during French exploratory surveys around New Caledonia (
Séret, 1997
), and later in 2003 during the NORFANZ voyage, an internationally funded survey of the Lord Howe Rise and Norfolk Ridge (
Williams et al. , 2006
).

Nothing is known of the biology of G. s u l u e n s i s but it may have a similar habitat, reproductive strategy and food habit to its congener.
Gollum attenuatus
matures at about 700 mm TL in both sexes (
Yano, 1993 a
) and reaches 1092 mm TL (
Yano, 1993 b
). It usually has a litter size of two. Each ovum produces ca 50–100 ova, of which ca 30–80 are enclosed in an egg capsule. Only one embryo develops in each capsule, and the undeveloped ova are ingested and passed to an external yolk sac that produces nutrition for the developing embryo (
Yano, 1993 a
).
Gollum attenuatus
lives near the bottom and feeds mainly on fishes (small sharks and teleosts), as well as small benthic invertebrates (
Yano, 1993 b
).
